These create plenty of traffic to observe and all three work well with delays at
sDelay = 230-260uSec so the timing is very tolerant, yet robust.  In this example 
run there is a requirement of 15 header hits, and 9 bytes for each packet to run the
system a bit harder to show up any bad timings up quicker. Early samples show only
one transmitter being received, and last samples show bad data, so best to pick
around the middle of the best packets, in this case 245uS.

If you use this program I suggest you start off with a lower value for header hits,
say 10 and maybe about 5 bytes.  You can make it more demanding when you get your
sDelay in range and know what polarity is working, and trying them in the 
DebugManchester.ino version and building your own system from there.

If you wanted a more critical test and you know how your system validates packets eg
multiple repeats or checksums, then you could program that into the DebugAuto.ino
version so that any errors are also reported.  The packets below do not have any
checking on them. All this means is that the program has considered that they have
met the Manchester waveform satisfactorily over duration of the packet.  There
could easily bit errors at either end of the delay setting and of course from time
